		<description><![CDATA[This is fascinating Max. I&#039;ve also found Bernadette&#039;s story absorbing and have often wondered how to &#039;retrieve&#039; the shamanic or visionary experiences of women in Catholic tradition from the patriarchal and dogmatic trappings that framed their reception. Teresa of Avila is another woman who moved between the Carmelite and marrano (forced Jewish convert) traditions and family matriarchies. And perhaps some other seer heritage defined as heresy.]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This is fascinating Max. I&#8217;ve also found Bernadette&#8217;s story absorbing and have often wondered how to &#8216;retrieve&#8217; the shamanic or visionary experiences of women in Catholic tradition from the patriarchal and dogmatic trappings that framed their reception. Teresa of Avila is another woman who moved between the Carmelite and marrano (forced Jewish convert) traditions and family matriarchies. And perhaps some other seer heritage defined as heresy.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
